1
00:00:56,233 --> 00:00:57,234
What have we got?

2
00:00:57,267 --> 00:00:58,199
Male, age 10,

3
00:00:58,200 --> 00:00:59,076
acute abdomen,

4
00:00:59,100 --> 00:00:59,966
low blood pressure,

5
00:00:59,967 --> 00:01:00,932
possible shock.

6
00:01:00,933 --> 00:01:02,499
Looks like
a ruptured viscous.

7
00:01:02,500 --> 00:01:03,699
Run the blood work.

8
00:01:03,700 --> 00:01:05,611
Call surgery. Look, stay
in the waiting room.

9
00:01:05,633 --> 00:01:08,409
I'll be back
to tell you how he's doing.

10
00:01:36,067 --> 00:01:40,015
It's good to be able to come in
here and kneel alone.

11
00:01:45,233 --> 00:01:47,932
But sometimes...

12
00:01:47,933 --> 00:01:50,066
You need somebody

13
00:01:50,067 --> 00:01:53,399
to kneel beside you.

14
00:01:53,400 --> 00:01:55,166
May I?

15
00:01:55,167 --> 00:01:56,942
Please.

16
00:02:01,700 --> 00:02:03,532
I'm Alexander.

17
00:02:03,533 --> 00:02:05,274
John Brighton.

18
00:02:07,533 --> 00:02:11,699
It's my son, Kyle.

19
00:02:11,700 --> 00:02:15,132
His appendix burst

20
00:02:15,133 --> 00:02:17,366
and...

21
00:02:17,367 --> 00:02:18,866
I'm. . .afraid...

22
00:02:18,867 --> 00:02:20,869
of losing him.

23
00:02:22,833 --> 00:02:25,199
Sometimes our
burdens are <i>so</i> heavy

24
00:02:25,200 --> 00:02:27,432
that we can't
find the words

25
00:02:27,433 --> 00:02:29,777
to express what's
in our hearts.

26
00:02:31,400 --> 00:02:34,574
Do you mind if I say
a prayer for your son?

27
00:02:34,600 --> 00:02:36,876
Please.

28
00:02:36,900 --> 00:02:41,576
You told us, Lord if there was
anything we wanted,

29
00:02:41,600 --> 00:02:44,866
to come to you.

30
00:02:44,867 --> 00:02:46,966
Well, we come to you now.

31
00:02:46,967 --> 00:02:49,880
This is John, Lord,

32
00:02:49,900 --> 00:02:54,599
whose heart is burdened
and heavy-laden.

33
00:02:54,600 --> 00:02:59,600
He has a son, Kyle,
whom he loves very much

34
00:02:59,633 --> 00:03:04,199
and Kyle is sick,
Kyle is deathly sick,

35
00:03:04,200 --> 00:03:08,376
<i>so</i> we're asking you Lord,
to save Kyle.

36
00:03:08,400 --> 00:03:10,437
And we know you can do it

37
00:03:10,467 --> 00:03:12,674
through the blood
that you shed for us.

38
00:03:12,700 --> 00:03:15,010
Heal him Lord...

39
00:03:15,033 --> 00:03:17,432
and heal him now.

40
00:03:17,433 --> 00:03:19,276
This we ask in the name

41
00:03:19,300 --> 00:03:21,066
of thy son, Jesus.

42
00:03:21,067 --> 00:03:22,944
Amen.

43
00:03:24,633 --> 00:03:26,699
Well...

44
00:03:26,700 --> 00:03:28,966
We've laid it out before him

45
00:03:28,967 --> 00:03:31,538
like he told us.

46
00:03:31,567 --> 00:03:34,707
The rest. . .
Is up to him.

47
00:03:36,533 --> 00:03:38,570
Thank you.

48
00:03:38,600 --> 00:03:42,199
Thank you <i>so</i> much,
Alexander.

49
00:03:42,200 --> 00:03:45,374
Are you a
chaplain here?

50
00:03:45,400 --> 00:03:47,539
<i>No, no.</i>

51
00:03:47,567 --> 00:03:52,516
But I've
come here many times.

52
00:03:52,533 --> 00:03:55,912
Many times but...

53
00:03:55,933 --> 00:04:00,905
I, ah. . .Won't be
coming anymore.

54
00:04:00,933 --> 00:04:02,640
Not now.

55
00:04:02,667 --> 00:04:05,204
What were you here
to pray about?

56
00:04:05,233 --> 00:04:10,233
My wife. . .My Marjorie.

57
00:04:10,367 --> 00:04:13,678
She had cancer...

58
00:04:13,700 --> 00:04:18,046
And she passed away
this morning.

59
00:04:18,067 --> 00:04:20,104
I'm sorry.

60
00:04:21,867 --> 00:04:26,441
John, you are a lucky man.

61
00:04:26,467 --> 00:04:30,381
Marjorie and I, we wanted to have
kids but we never did.

62
00:04:30,400 --> 00:04:33,132
You have a family.

63
00:04:33,133 --> 00:04:36,342
Love your family, John.

64
00:04:36,367 --> 00:04:39,280
Love them
with everything you got.

65
00:04:41,133 --> 00:04:46,879
And about Kyle. . .trust him.

66
00:04:48,133 --> 00:04:50,511
Kyle will be all right.

67
00:04:52,367 --> 00:04:55,712
Everett Wayne Anderson.

68
00:05:00,033 --> 00:05:05,244
Terry Ernestine Anderson,

69
00:05:09,133 --> 00:05:10,976
where's the camera?

70
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:12,707
I gave it
to you.

71
00:05:15,400 --> 00:05:17,346
It's hanging
on your shoulder!

72
00:05:17,367 --> 00:05:20,541
Oh, oh! I don't believe it.

73
00:05:20,567 --> 00:05:23,332
If you need help locating
your sunglasses later,

74
00:05:23,333 --> 00:05:25,266
I'd be happy
to help you look.

75
00:05:25,267 --> 00:05:26,974
Thank you
very much.

76
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:29,037
Kyle Alexander Brighton.

77
00:05:53,300 --> 00:05:55,632
How are those burgers
coming, pastor?

78
00:05:55,633 --> 00:05:57,732
Well, John, they're
sort of a burnt offering.

79
00:05:57,733 --> 00:06:00,099
I thought Kyle
ate a lot.

80
00:06:00,100 --> 00:06:03,732
He does, but now you've got 50
Kyles together in one place.

81
00:06:03,733 --> 00:06:07,799
Reminds me of the movie
"the thing that ate Pittsburgh."

82
00:06:07,800 --> 00:06:10,599
So anyway, this account is sitting
there

83
00:06:10,600 --> 00:06:13,432
like this, like this big plum ready to
be picked off the tree

84
00:06:13,433 --> 00:06:15,599
you know what
your old man says?

85
00:06:15,600 --> 00:06:17,932
"I think we should stop
and think about it."

86
00:06:17,933 --> 00:06:19,932
What is that
all about, Kyle?

87
00:06:19,933 --> 00:06:21,913
You're majoring
in business, right?

88
00:06:21,933 --> 00:06:23,966
That's right uncle Phil.

89
00:06:23,967 --> 00:06:25,275
Here's your first lesson...

90
00:06:28,733 --> 00:06:31,399
Great-- each minute Kyle
talks with my brother

91
00:06:31,400 --> 00:06:34,006
it takes me an hour
to deprogram him.

92
00:06:34,033 --> 00:06:36,707
I call it uncle Phil detox.

93
00:06:36,733 --> 00:06:39,599
Listen to me. Candi and I want to
give you something that's

94
00:06:39,600 --> 00:06:42,137
well, a little something
that's real...

95
00:06:42,167 --> 00:06:43,599
A little going away present.

96
00:06:43,600 --> 00:06:44,977
No, no...

97
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:48,099
C' mon Kyle, look at it as an
investment in your future.

98
00:06:48,100 --> 00:06:50,478
Now remember, if you want
something in life

99
00:06:50,500 --> 00:06:52,810
you got to go for it.

100
00:06:52,833 --> 00:06:54,676
C' mon Kyle,
pull harder!

101
00:06:54,700 --> 00:06:57,232
Ohhhh!!

102
00:06:57,233 --> 00:06:59,804
You were right, Teri.

103
00:06:59,833 --> 00:07:03,178
I didn't think it would
work but, sure enough!

104
00:07:04,767 --> 00:07:06,866
Ah, you're a good kid, Kyle.

105
00:07:06,867 --> 00:07:08,312
I like you.

106
00:07:08,333 --> 00:07:10,732
Did you see what
Phil did to Kyle?

107
00:07:10,733 --> 00:07:13,866
You and Phil are just
like your dad-- always...

108
00:07:13,867 --> 00:07:17,099
Don't ever say that--
Phil's like dad, I'm not.

109
00:07:17,100 --> 00:07:21,332
Hey, this is me remember,
the one who's on your side.

110
00:07:21,333 --> 00:07:24,299
Why can't he be committed
to one woman and settle down?

111
00:07:24,300 --> 00:07:26,280
Look at him, he's got
a different woman

112
00:07:26,300 --> 00:07:28,280
every time we see him.

113
00:07:28,300 --> 00:07:30,746
John, Phil is not
your responsibility.

114
00:07:30,767 --> 00:07:34,078
Let God handle it.

115
00:07:44,200 --> 00:07:49,200
Ah, wait...

116
00:07:49,833 --> 00:07:51,608
<i>I'm...</i>

117
00:07:52,933 --> 00:07:55,966
I'm winded--
I'm never winded.

118
00:07:55,967 --> 00:07:59,299
Well, you know what they say
about growing old.

119
00:07:59,300 --> 00:08:02,166
No, what do they
say about growing old?

120
00:08:02,167 --> 00:08:05,766
Actually, they don't say anything at
all.

121
00:08:05,767 --> 00:08:08,299
But I do remember
you saying

122
00:08:08,300 --> 00:08:10,099
that I'm the one
who's growing old

123
00:08:10,100 --> 00:08:11,932
while you stay
the same age.

124
00:08:11,933 --> 00:08:15,005
That's true--you're a cradle
robber. I'm going to go back.

125
00:08:15,033 --> 00:08:17,099
You want me to go with you?

126
00:08:17,100 --> 00:08:18,909
<i>No, no. No. No.</i>

127
00:08:18,933 --> 00:08:21,332
You need
the exercise.

128
00:08:21,333 --> 00:08:24,314
You know what they say
about middle-aged men?

129
00:08:24,333 --> 00:08:26,332
What do they say?

130
00:08:26,333 --> 00:08:28,466
The legs are the first to go.

131
00:08:28,467 --> 00:08:30,003
Oh, thanks a lot.

132
00:08:30,033 --> 00:08:32,032
You going to
be okay?

133
00:08:32,033 --> 00:08:35,199
I'm fine-- I may lie down
a bit, but I'm fine.

134
00:08:35,200 --> 00:08:37,544
All right. See you
in a while.

135
00:08:42,100 --> 00:08:45,104
Oh, Kyle. . .you forgot Johnny.

136
00:08:45,133 --> 00:08:47,113
Ma, I don't
need Johnny.

137
00:08:47,133 --> 00:08:49,113
But you've always taken him.

138
00:08:49,133 --> 00:08:51,132
I know, but,
keep him here.

139
00:08:51,133 --> 00:08:52,966
I'll be home
lots of weekends,

140
00:08:52,967 --> 00:08:54,866
don't worry, with big bags
of laundry.

141
00:08:54,867 --> 00:08:56,574
So things won't
change that much.

142
00:08:56,600 --> 00:08:58,170
I love you, sweetheart.

143
00:08:58,200 --> 00:08:59,679
I love you too,
mom.

144
00:08:59,700 --> 00:09:01,338
Don't worry.

145
00:09:01,367 --> 00:09:03,904
I'll tell you about
what worries me.

146
00:09:03,933 --> 00:09:05,674
What's that, dad?

147
00:09:05,700 --> 00:09:07,866
Well, you letting yourself
be influenced

148
00:09:07,867 --> 00:09:10,040
by your uncle Phil's <i>school</i>
of business.

149
00:09:10,067 --> 00:09:11,478
Dad.

150
00:09:11,500 --> 00:09:13,999
Now remember, living by God's
principles is not exactly

151
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:16,399
on the top of his list
of priorities.

152
00:09:16,400 --> 00:09:18,599
Even though he's my business
partner and my brother

153
00:09:18,600 --> 00:09:20,671
we always don't see
eye-to-eye on things.

154
00:09:20,700 --> 00:09:22,043
Dad, don't worry.

155
00:09:22,067 --> 00:09:23,732
I'm not as dumb
as I look.

156
00:09:23,733 --> 00:09:25,337
Dad, I can see
what's going on.

157
00:09:25,367 --> 00:09:26,632
Don't worry.

158
00:09:26,633 --> 00:09:28,432
I love you son.

159
00:09:28,433 --> 00:09:30,099
I'm proud of you.

160
00:09:30,100 --> 00:09:32,399
I love you too, dad.

161
00:09:32,400 --> 00:09:34,004
See you squirt!

162
00:09:34,033 --> 00:09:36,199
I'm almost 16-- you can't
call me that anymore!

163
00:09:36,200 --> 00:09:39,232
Okay--try not to flunk out
of <i>school</i> this year, okay?

164
00:09:39,233 --> 00:09:43,147
Oh right, and how many academic
scholarships did Mr. IQ get?

165
00:09:43,167 --> 00:09:44,669
Huh?

166
00:09:48,033 --> 00:09:50,980
Now they decide
to get along.

167
00:09:52,900 --> 00:09:55,141
Now get out of here,
will ya?

168
00:09:55,167 --> 00:09:57,773
I love you guys.

169
00:10:04,400 --> 00:10:06,710
Fight you for his room?

170
00:10:06,733 --> 00:10:09,475
Don't you mean
my new study?

171
00:10:09,500 --> 00:10:10,672
Oh!!!

172
00:10:13,733 --> 00:10:16,066
They're right
in the palm of our hand.

173
00:10:16,067 --> 00:10:18,299
All we have to do is
squeeze them a little bit.

174
00:10:18,300 --> 00:10:20,599
C' mon John,
use that charm of yours.

175
00:10:20,600 --> 00:10:22,232
Slow down
will you?

176
00:10:22,233 --> 00:10:23,769
Don't use such
a big club.

177
00:10:23,800 --> 00:10:25,245
What do you mean?

178
00:10:25,267 --> 00:10:27,566
I mean, you don't have to steamroll
every deal, Phil,

179
00:10:27,567 --> 00:10:29,774
I want you to walk a little softer
on this one.

180
00:10:29,800 --> 00:10:31,541
Okay? For once!

181
00:10:31,567 --> 00:10:33,466
It's the way
to do business.

182
00:10:33,467 --> 00:10:35,066
It's the way
you do business.

183
00:10:35,067 --> 00:10:37,199
It's not my way, not
like the Callahan deal.

184
00:10:37,200 --> 00:10:39,232
What about
the Callahan deal?

185
00:10:39,233 --> 00:10:41,399
You promised them the world, then
we couldn't deliver.

186
00:10:41,400 --> 00:10:44,006
No firm could-- you
misled them, Phil.

187
00:10:44,033 --> 00:10:45,944
Lied, really.

188
00:10:45,967 --> 00:10:48,243
Oooo-- here <i>comes</i>
the moral police again.

189
00:10:48,267 --> 00:10:50,247
Yeah, I lied! Everybody does.

190
00:10:50,267 --> 00:10:52,399
If our word is
no good,

191
00:10:52,400 --> 00:10:54,866
we can't expect their word
to be any good,

192
00:10:54,867 --> 00:10:57,066
then nobody is committed
to the deal

193
00:10:57,067 --> 00:10:59,066
on either side
of the table.

194
00:10:59,067 --> 00:11:01,604
We do not approach
this deal that way.

195
00:11:02,400 --> 00:11:04,004
Fine.

196
00:11:07,533 --> 00:11:09,532
Would you mind knocking?

197
00:11:09,533 --> 00:11:11,099
What are you wearing???

198
00:11:11,100 --> 00:11:12,909
Stuff for school.

199
00:11:12,933 --> 00:11:16,032
Well, you can just take it back to
wherever you got it.

200
00:11:16,033 --> 00:11:18,966
You're not going to go out of this
house dressed like that.

201
00:11:18,967 --> 00:11:21,732
Why not? All the girls
dress like this.

202
00:11:21,733 --> 00:11:23,932
Well you're not going
to dress like this.

203
00:11:23,933 --> 00:11:26,299
What do you want me to do,
wear skirts down to my ankles?

204
00:11:26,300 --> 00:11:28,732
Just do as I tell you,
Teri-- that's enough!!

205
00:11:28,733 --> 00:11:31,499
Look, just because your baby left
for college doesn't mean

206
00:11:31,500 --> 00:11:33,632
you can take your
frustrations out on me.

207
00:11:33,633 --> 00:11:35,442
I'm just doing
nothing...

208
00:11:39,733 --> 00:11:41,499
Stop it. . .Stop it.

209
00:11:41,500 --> 00:11:42,979
Stop it! Stop it!

210
00:11:45,500 --> 00:11:47,343
Stop it!
Slop it!

211
00:11:58,167 --> 00:11:59,299
Hi, honey.

212
00:11:59,300 --> 00:12:00,370
Hi, sweetheart.

213
00:12:00,400 --> 00:12:01,766
How was
your day?

214
00:12:01,767 --> 00:12:04,166
Good, I think. We're waiting
to find out any time

215
00:12:04,167 --> 00:12:06,340
about that Atlantic Petroleum
account-- we're really close.

216
00:12:06,367 --> 00:12:08,074
Where is the mail?

217
00:12:08,100 --> 00:12:10,080
I don't know,
maybe Teri has it.

218
00:12:10,100 --> 00:12:11,166
Has what?

219
00:12:11,167 --> 00:12:12,202
The mail.

220
00:12:12,233 --> 00:12:13,999
How could I have it?
I just got home.

221
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:16,412
You're kidding. That's great!
we got the account.

222
00:12:16,433 --> 00:12:18,066
Oh, wonderful.

223
00:12:18,067 --> 00:12:19,808
Well, I found the mail.

224
00:12:19,833 --> 00:12:22,712
It's right here where it should be--
next to the margarine?

225
00:12:22,733 --> 00:12:24,566
How did it get in there?

226
00:12:24,567 --> 00:12:26,466
Hold on a second, Phil.

227
00:12:26,467 --> 00:12:28,071
Don't look at me.

228
00:12:28,100 --> 00:12:30,666
Well, I didn't put it
in there, John?

229
00:12:30,667 --> 00:12:33,399
Ellen, don't look at me,
it had to be you.

230
00:12:33,400 --> 00:12:35,666
Unless the mail carrier decided to
put it in there.

231
00:12:35,667 --> 00:12:37,566
Ellen, you're getting
nuts on us.

232
00:12:37,567 --> 00:12:40,104
No, she put the mail
in the refrigerator.

233
00:12:40,133 --> 00:12:41,942
Yeah, that's right--

234
00:12:41,967 --> 00:12:44,914
probably trying to freeze
some of my assets.

235
00:12:44,933 --> 00:12:46,932
At least what I've got.

236
00:12:46,933 --> 00:12:48,970
Well, this is great!

237
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:49,535
Our next speaker was awarded
Harrison Elementary's

238
00:12:49,633 --> 00:12:51,544
Our next speaker was awarded
Harrison Elementary's

239
00:12:51,567 --> 00:12:53,740
teacher of the year this spring.

240
00:12:53,767 --> 00:12:56,932
I've heard rumors she might run for
<i>school</i> board next year,

241
00:12:56,933 --> 00:12:59,832
and I want to go
on record right now

242
00:12:59,833 --> 00:13:03,066
and say that I will personally
campaign for

243
00:13:03,067 --> 00:13:06,732
anyone who runs
against her...

244
00:13:06,733 --> 00:13:09,509
Because we simply can't
lose her as a teacher.

245
00:13:09,533 --> 00:13:12,776
Please welcome, Ellen Brighton.

246
00:13:20,167 --> 00:13:24,047
After 6 long months
of hard work from all of us,

247
00:13:24,067 --> 00:13:26,799
well, maybe not all of 'em.

248
00:13:26,800 --> 00:13:28,746
I think we finally reached

249
00:13:28,767 --> 00:13:30,872
the next plateau
with Atlantic Petroleum.

250
00:13:30,900 --> 00:13:33,676
This time we finally struck oil!

251
00:13:35,367 --> 00:13:37,866
Now if you'll open your
presentation...

252
00:13:37,867 --> 00:13:40,732
If every teacher had someone
as supportive as Valerie,

253
00:13:40,733 --> 00:13:43,907
this profession would be
a lot easier.

254
00:13:49,533 --> 00:13:51,410
I'd like to...

255
00:13:53,233 --> 00:13:55,873
I'd like to, um...

256
00:13:55,900 --> 00:13:58,881
I'd like to talk
to you today...

257
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:05,799
I-I I must need glasses,

258
00:14:05,800 --> 00:14:08,076
